The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation
		 Friday, May 28, 2004 				 Rights onus on colonels
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT																								New Delhi, May 27: The army headquarters has asked officers of the rank of colonels to look into allegations of human rights violations by the force, General .C. Vij has told the National Human Rights Commission.																								The army chief wrote to the NHRC after its chairperson, Justice A.S. Anand, met him earlier this week and said the commission was deeply concerned about allegations of human rights violations by security forces. Justice Anand sought a report from General Vij detailing the action taken by the army on such charges.																								In his letter, General Vij said officers of the rank of colonels have been specifically designated to monitor and follow up cases of human rights violations reported against army personnel at the levels of different formations  corps, divisional and counter-insurgency.																								In Jammu and Kashmir at least, battalion commanders and their deputies have had additional responsibilities to look into charges of atrocities for several years now. The army headquarters had launched a drive under General Shankar Roy Choudhury, now a Rajya Sabha member, to sensitise officers and troops to the issue of human rights. He had formulated a code of ethics for troops in counter-insurgency theatres.																								In his letter to the NHRC, General Vij said the army was taking cognizance not only of the violations reported by the NHRC but also those by all other sources, including the ones reported in the media. A total of 131 personnel of different ranks had been punished on charges of violating human rights.																								The NHRC had noted that between 1990-1999, 1,039 cases of human rights violations at an average of 104 cases a year had been recorded. Between 2000 and March 2004, the total number of reported cases was 346 at an average of 81 per year.
